task.summary: Default task
Working with CollectionView

Changed the validation length on the password field in the loginform to allow for shorter passwords. Added more info to the repr of Collection.
A lot of stuff in the CollectionView to create new collections and such. Changed the templates to display more info and display the correct forms.
Changed the info on the mainpage depending on if you are logged in or not. Must add csrf_tokens to all forms, wounder if there are any other ways to do it?
Working around the anonymous user that flask-login uses when the user isn't logged in. Should work now with the added is_active calls.

Renamed Group to Collection in __repr__ for Collection so that it actually representes what it is. We do not need to remember the user with cookies, so set it explicitly.
Set the route_base to shorter things, but will probably not keep it. This meant that I had to change the forms since they need to use the correct route.
Also changed the errorhandler for 404 to give a better errormessage for debugging.

Removed the block for the title since that was a little extreme I think, instead it uses justa variable instead. Changed all views and templates to represent this. Changed the register view to not allow the same usernames and at the same time alert you about it.
Removed the Classy logout class since it only needed a simple route, nothing more than that.

Removed the "Du accessade sidan med get istället för post" since it did nothing useful. Changed the layout to always include login/logout things. Started using flask.g to give access to current_user to not have to pass it in to every template, this uses @app.before_request to set up g.user to current_user.
Persistant login/logout ability is very handy and something that just must be there, so it had to be implemented.
Updated the Product and Sprint backlog to better reflect what Im doing. Should start working on the testspecification and such, but it's difficult when there are areas that are missing.

Changed the length of the validators to allow for something to login with it's 5 character password. Added a LinkPostForm to allow for linkposts as well as textposts. Added the LogoutView again since it was having some problems, probably just didn't import it as I should. Changed main.html to user g.user instead of user since it will break if no one is logged in. Added the linkform to to new_post.html. Added the correct url_for since I changed the view.
Working on implementing categories, creating and viewing at first and then posting to them. Created the basic templates but they aren't sufficient since they need to do much more.
More work on the categories.
Odd names on categoryid and categoryname, should change those later.
More work on categories, getting posting to work. Changed the models so that status and type isn't forced, that way I don't get errors all the time when those fks are missing.
Problems with the creation of posts on categories.

Changed from db.String to postgresql.BYTEA instead since I changed encrypt function to return bytes instead of string. Added a getsalt function instead. We want to be able to view a post in a category, so added a function for that. Had a small problem in main.html where i used username instead of id in the url_for.
Renamed the variables from id to categoryname since we are going to use that and not the id of the category.
Adding some more stuff with categories, displaying all of them on the front page. Some assertions in views
Adding moderation slowly. Hopefully this works well. Much debugging.
SOmething done in the Basic Vision and working with the templates. Seeing if the routes should have trailing slash or not, we'll see.
Changed from collections being under /c/ to categories beging under /c/. More accessible I believe.
Added a collections template for the users own collections. Now /p/new redirects to the category that the user chose when the post is created.
Added a macro for rendering posts so that it can be used by all templates that need to display a summary of a post. Macros are nice, so I will probably use them more.
Switched to using the new macro for some of the templates and added more stuff to them, more like it's supposed to be.
Added description to a few files.
No it's not possible to go to the register or login screen if you are already logged in. Instead you just get redirected to the index-page.

Changed some values in the sprint backlog, logging worked time. Renamed a relation from collections to posts since that's what it is. Implemented a render_collection macro and uses it on in collection.html to display a collection.
render_collection_dense macro allows us to render a large amount of collections, such at in /collection/. We do not need to display all posts, just how many there are, and links to the collections.

Added markdown support. Will start using this for the user inputs. Added some ugly borders around the render_post and render_collection_dense macros to allow me to see where they are. Use the render_collection_dense macro to render the current_users collections.
Getting a problem with the removal of objects, somehow I'm working with 2 different sessions, so I will have to fix that ifrst. Updated documentation.
Changed some imports which should improve the programming a bit.

Added a DeletePostForm, which probably will get renamed to DeleteForm, which only has a button. This allows us to delete things in the templates, such as posts and collections. Changed the collection_has_post and category_has_moderator to have a composite primary_key. Hopefully this works as intended. This allows us to edit the posts and not just view them. Added a BlogView that just returns CategoryView.get(self, 'blog'). This is so that I can have a development blog easily. Importing func from sqlalchemy so that I can use the func.lower for categoryname. This should be changed so that categoryname is always lowercase, but I haven't done that yet. TODO. The same in view_post, which has grown quite a bit. Will have to tackle that soon. Added macros to render blog, collection and such. These should be renamed and fixed, but they work right now. New blog template. Small changes to the other templates.
Removed some warnings about comments in some files.

Updated Sprint Backlog. changed the categoryname to use the lowercase version. This way we do not need to check it later, and the url will always use the lowercase anyway. Added the categorytitle to the create_category template.
Adding categorytitle to the form. add_moderator shell.
Changed some things, idk what.

Adding posts to collections is now possible, but I want to be able to do it some other way. Lets see how that owkrs out. At this moment it's not possible to remove the posts, but that should be solved some time.
Simplified the adding of posts to collections, which also should mean that it is easier to remove posts.

Decided to only use a single view for adding posts, which simplifies the logic and removes unnecessary code. Updating the postcount on a user so that every new post adds 1 to it. Renamed groupid to collectionid, it was a remnant from when collections were called groups.

Updated some forms. Checking to see if the user is in category.moderators or post.createdby so that they can remove the post. Added another macro to render post_without the delete button, since we don't want that if you aren't allowed to remove it.
Changed some macros to compress the displayed data a bit.
Adding moderators should now be possible via the /c/<categoryname>/moderators/add route. Takes a username and adds it. TODO: Error checking

AddModeratorForm added. Implemented the add moderator functionality. Swapped out All moderators to a macro instead. Added some stuff to the createanddrop so that there are some statues and some types.
Working towards adding links to collections.

* Relation between User and Status so that we can access the Status name without doing Status.query.get(statusid).statusname. * Change from only display a number but now with a explanation. * Added some descriptions on the forms. * Added statusname for the user page.

* Comment form. Now we can comment on posts, not on comments, but it's a step in the right direction. Should add a relationship between comments aswell so that I can access them eaasier. * Changed from PostView:get, id to PostView:get, postid. * Stopped using render_post_with_delete and just use the render_post and render_field macros instead. Much better and nicer. * Comments in collection.html and changed a action in a form.
* AddModeratorForm and CommentForm * Renamed id to postid and added a print statement.
* Added docstrings to all views

* Had some problem with SQLAlchemy, which seems to be solved now, IDK if it is though. * Since I changed CollectionView:get from id to collection id I needed to change that in the templates as well. *
